05135nam a22006495i 9780887555404DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875554047 a10.1515/97808875554042doi  a(DE-B1597)664623  a(OCoLC)1408682157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aE96.5b.T75 2016eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.004/972231 aTruth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Knock on the Door :bThe Essential History of Residential Schools from the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada, Edited and Abridged /cTruth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerceptions on Truth and Reconciliation ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tResidential Schools in Canada -- tChronology -- tIntroduction -- tThe History -- tThe School Experience -- tThe Legacy -- tReconciliation -- tCalls to Action -- tGabekana -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“It can start with a knock on the door one morning. It is the local Indian agent, or the parish priest, or, perhaps, a Mounted Police officer.” So began the school experience of many Indigenous children in Canada for more than a hundred years, and so begins the history of residential schools prepared by the Truth & Reconciliation Commission of Canada (TRC). Between 2008 and 2015, the TRC provided opportunities for individuals, families, and communities to share their experiences of residential schools and released several reports based on 7000 survivor statements and five million documents from government, churches, and schools, as well as a solid grounding in secondary sources. A Knock on the Door, published in collaboration with the National Research Centre for Truth & Reconciliation, gathers material from the several reports the TRC has produced to present the essential history and legacy of residential schools in a concise and accessible package that includes new materials to help inform and contextualize the journey to reconciliation that Canadians are now embarked upon. Survivor and former National Chief of the Assembly First Nations, Phil Fontaine, provides a Foreword, and an Afterword introduces the holdings and opportunities of the National Centre for Truth & Reconciliation, home to the archive of recordings, and documents collected by the TRC. As Aimée Craft writes in the Afterword, knowing the historical backdrop of residential schooling and its legacy is essential to the work of reconciliation. In the past, agents of the Canadian state knocked on the doors of Indigenous families to take the children to school. Now, the Survivors have shared their truths and knocked back. It is time for Canadians to open the door to mutual understanding, respect, and reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North America - Canada - Social conditions - 20th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducationzCanadaxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxCrimes againstzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxHistory. 0aOff-reservation boarding schoolszCanadaxHistory. 0aTruth commissionszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aCraft, Aimée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is